{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The O(n²) Problem"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Standard self-attention computes a score for every pair of tokens. For a sequence of length "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "n"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", this requires an "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "n × n"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " matrix — O(n²) in both time and memory. A sequence of 100 tokens produces a 10,000-element attention matrix. A sequence of 100,000 tokens (long document) would need 10 billion elements. Efficient transformers address this quadratic bottleneck through several complementary strategies."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Efficient transformer techniques: sparse/local attention, linear attention, FlashAttention tiling, grouped-query attention, and summary comparison table"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sparse and Local Attention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest reduction: instead of attending to all "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "n"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " positions, each token attends only to a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "window of w nearest positions"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". This reduces complexity to O(n·w). Longformer (Beltagy et al. 2020) combines local windowed attention with a handful of global tokens (e.g. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "[CLS]"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for classification) that can attend to everything:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import LongformerModel, LongformerTokenizer\nimport torch\n\ntokenizer = LongformerTokenizer.from_pretrained('allenai/longformer-base-4096')\nmodel     = LongformerModel.from_pretrained('allenai/longformer-base-4096')\n\ntext = \"Long document text here \" * 200  # >512 tokens\ninputs = tokenizer(text, return_tensors='pt', max_length=4096, truncation=True)\n\n# attention_mask: 1=local, 2=global\n# Make [CLS] (token 0) attend globally\nattention_mask = inputs['attention_mask'].clone()\nattention_mask[0, 0] = 2  # global attention for [CLS]\n\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    out = model(**inputs, attention_mask=attention_mask)\nprint(out.last_hidden_state.shape)  # (1, T, 768)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mistral 7B uses "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "sliding window attention (SWA)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " with a window of 4,096 tokens. Information from beyond the window can still propagate across layers — after L layers, a token can effectively attend up to L·w positions away."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "FlashAttention: IO-Aware Exact Attention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "FlashAttention (Dao et al. 2022) does not reduce the theoretical O(n²) operation count — it still computes the exact same attention matrix. Instead it eliminates the bottleneck of "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "slow GPU memory (HBM) reads and writes"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Standard attention materialises the full n × n matrix in HBM; FlashAttention tiles the computation into blocks that fit in fast on-chip SRAM (shared memory), computing the result block-by-block without ever writing the full matrix to HBM."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The key algorithmic ingredient is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "online softmax"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": the softmax normaliser is computed incrementally as blocks are processed, using the \"safe softmax\" identity that lets you update a running max and running sum without re-scanning prior blocks."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{softmax}(x_1, \\ldots, x_n)_i = \\frac{e^{x_i - m}}{\\sum_j e^{x_j - m}}, \\quad m = \\max_j x_j"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In practice, FlashAttention is 2–4× faster than standard PyTorch attention at sequence length 2,048 and the speedup grows with sequence length. It is now the default in most LLM training frameworks and is enabled in PyTorch 2.0 via "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "F.scaled_dot_product_attention"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ":"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\nB, H, T, D = 2, 12, 2048, 64\nQ = torch.randn(B, H, T, D, device='cuda', dtype=torch.float16)\nK = torch.randn(B, H, T, D, device='cuda', dtype=torch.float16)\nV = torch.randn(B, H, T, D, device='cuda', dtype=torch.float16)\n\n# PyTorch 2.0 automatically uses FlashAttention if available\n# is_causal=True applies the causal mask efficiently (no explicit mask tensor needed)\nwith torch.backends.cuda.sdp_kernel(enable_flash=True):\n    out = F.scaled_dot_product_attention(Q, K, V, is_causal=True)\n\nprint(out.shape)  # (2, 12, 2048, 64)\n\n# Verify FlashAttention is being used\nwith torch.backends.cuda.sdp_kernel(enable_flash=True, enable_math=False, enable_mem_efficient=False):\n    # This will raise if FlashAttention is not available\n    out2 = F.scaled_dot_product_attention(Q, K, V, is_causal=True)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Multi-Query and Grouped-Query Attention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "At inference time, the main bottleneck is often not computation but the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "KV cache"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " — the stored keys and values for all previous tokens in the context. In standard multi-head attention (MHA) with H heads, the KV cache grows as 2 · H · T · d_head bytes per layer. For LLaMA-65B with H=64 heads and a 4K context, this is tens of gigabytes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Multi-Query Attention (MQA)"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": all H query heads share a single K and V head. KV cache shrinks by H×. Used in Falcon and PaLM."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Grouped-Query Attention (GQA)"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": Q heads are split into G groups; each group shares one K and V head. GQA with G=1 is MQA; G=H is MHA. LLaMA-2/3 and Mistral use G=8 (8 KV heads for 32 Q heads)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\nclass GroupedQueryAttention(nn.Module):\n    \"\"\"GQA: num_heads query heads, num_kv_heads key/value heads.\"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, d_model, num_heads, num_kv_heads):\n        super().__init__()\n        assert num_heads % num_kv_heads == 0\n        self.num_heads    = num_heads\n        self.num_kv_heads = num_kv_heads\n        self.groups       = num_heads // num_kv_heads\n        self.d_head       = d_model // num_heads\n\n        self.q_proj  = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n        self.k_proj  = nn.Linear(d_model, num_kv_heads * self.d_head, bias=False)\n        self.v_proj  = nn.Linear(d_model, num_kv_heads * self.d_head, bias=False)\n        self.o_proj  = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n\n    def forward(self, x):\n        B, T, _ = x.shape\n        Q = self.q_proj(x).view(B, T, self.num_heads,    self.d_head).transpose(1, 2)\n        K = self.k_proj(x).view(B, T, self.num_kv_heads, self.d_head).transpose(1, 2)\n        V = self.v_proj(x).view(B, T, self.num_kv_heads, self.d_head).transpose(1, 2)\n\n        # Expand K and V so each query head has a matching KV\n        K = K.repeat_interleave(self.groups, dim=1)  # (B, num_heads, T, d_head)\n        V = V.repeat_interleave(self.groups, dim=1)\n\n        out = F.scaled_dot_product_attention(Q, K, V, is_causal=True)\n        out = out.transpose(1, 2).reshape(B, T, -1)\n        return self.o_proj(out)\n\n# LLaMA-2 style: 32 query heads, 8 KV heads\ngqa = GroupedQueryAttention(d_model=4096, num_heads=32, num_kv_heads=8)\nprint(gqa.k_proj.weight.shape)   # (8*128, 4096) — 4× smaller than MHA"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Linear Attention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Linear attention approximates softmax attention using a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "kernel trick"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". The softmax can be written as:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{Attn}(Q,K,V) = \\frac{\\phi(Q)(\\phi(K)^\\top V)}{\\phi(Q)\\phi(K)^\\top \\mathbf{1}}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "By computing "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "φ(K)ᵀV"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " first (a d × d matrix independent of n), the total cost drops to O(n·d²). The Performer model uses random Fourier features to approximate the softmax kernel. In practice, linear attention models often fall slightly short of full attention quality, but recurrent formulations (Mamba, RWKV) that can be computed as O(n) scans are an active research direction."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Practical Guidance"
          }
        ]
      },
